data.text:
Post by Bernie on As part of a new effort for more consistent article quality on the wiki, we're going to begin attempting to fix articles up per request. Post any articles you feel need to be rewritten, revised, or reformatted. For tips on revising them yourself, see "Key Traits to a Good Article". There are plans to reward users who help revise articles, but it might be a while until such a system is implemented. Identifying Poorly-Written Articles First of all, make sure to read through the Wiki's article guidelines to identify what constitutes as a 'poorly-written' article. Here's an excerpt for the lazy : Plagiarism will not be tolerated and will ultimately result in a ban for repeat offenders; the entire article must be your own, though direct quotes are acceptable (so long as they don't comprise the majority of the article's content). Articles must be of a competent level of quality, with correct punctuation, spelling, paragraphing, etc. Pieces of lost media are only eligible for an article if they are relevant enough to warrant one, ie. they must be relatively known amongst the general public; if unsure of a potential article's eligibility, please contact a staff member. New articles for pieces of media that have already been found are allowed on a case-by-case basis, as the media in question must have been known about and considered lost for a significant period of time before it was found; if unsure of a potential article's eligibility, please contact a staff member. These 4 rules will be good for just identifying ineligible articles (though it's still suggested to read through the whole thing). If you have found one, but are unable / unsure how to rewrite it, please post it in this thread and it will be added to the list at the bottom. Adding the 'Needing Work' tags Once you've identified a bad article, be sure to tag it as 'Needing Work'. This way, it'll be easier to find and organize at first glance. Note that this is not necessary if you're editing it before submitting. All of the old code has been condensed into an easy template, so to mark an article as needing work, add the following to the top of the page: {{NeedingWork|heavy plagiarism}} The 'heavy plagiarism' can be changed for any number of reasons, like 'lack of content'. For custom alphabetization in listings, as with article titles that start with the word "the", you can add a sortkey to the end of it like this: {{NeedingWork|lack of content|Boondocks, The}} Key traits to a good article These few traits are what we'd like you to focus on when you begin revising articles. More will be added as time goes on 1. Infoboxes Infoboxes are one of the key traits of the wiki format. I've noticed a large number of articles lacking them, which I'm not sure is the reason to. If you notice an article lacking an infobox, please add it to the page. Here is the template: {{InfoboxLost |title=
Title of the Article
|image=Template.png |imagecaption=Image Caption. |status='''Status (ex: Found, Lost, Partially Lost)''' }} 2. Formatting One of the largest issues is formatting articles to be of consistent quality. This means using headers, table of contents, and properly embedding images. Here are two examples: [1] [2] Some shorter articles, or 'stubs', do not have enough information to warrant using headers. Use your best judgement on what makes the article easier to read and navigate. 3. Eligibility There are many articles that are simply ineligible for the site. This includes obscure but not lost pieces of media. If you are unsure of an article's eligibility for the site (i.e not truly being lost, non-important dubs, etc) post the article and a description of why you feel it may be ineligible. Submitting Articles to the Thread There will be two kinds of submissions in this thread: articles that need to be fixed, and articles that have been fixed. Here's a template that will hopefully help make the process easier: Article Name: Edited?: (Yes) (No) Categories: Summary: Link: And here's an example of it's usage. Article Name: A Day With SpongeBob SquarePants Edited?: (Yes) (No) Categories: Lost Animation Summary: Formatting Link: lostmediawiki.com/A_Day_With_SpongeBob_SquarePants:_The_Movie_(Unproduced_Direct-To-DVD_Movie;_2011) Articles needing to be revised: See also: lostmediawiki.com/Special:SpecialPages & lostmediawiki.com/Category:Needing_work 1 101% Spooky Whizbang! with Henry and June (partially found Nickelodeon Halloween block;
